{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_madison_ver01/data/sn95047168/00541310514/1949061701/0192.xml":{"full_text":"Union County djinn's\nLEX GREEN. Publisher Editor-In-Chief\nPublished Every Friday at lake Butler, Florida\nEntered as second class mail matter April 8, 1921, at the Post\nOffice at Lake Butler, Florida under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE\n$2.00 per year\u2014-In Advance\n^-^Q MEMm'^^/? $1.25 six months\u2014in advance\nFLORIDA PRESS Advertising Rates Cheerfully\nfurnished at this office\nA''\u00b0^'^T lON NATIONAL EDITORIAL\nForeign Gifts\nPlank Four m President Truman's four-point Foreign Policy is\nshaping up for consideration by the Congress, This plank\no ptoghun is tor the relief, upbuilding, enlightenment and ad\nvancement of underprivileged areas and people of the World.\nIhr plan has a noble purpose but its realization is a cat of adif\niien. color. It purposes to take from the Treasury of the\nIneed States billions of dollars and from rhe warelbouses, factor-\nginneries and mines, billion -of tons of useable goods. This\nrimey and thoe goods, according to the plan, are to be loanded\ng>en for the advancement, of peoples and countries in Europe,\nAsa and Africa.\nP true that a miall portion of it may be planned for utilizat\nion or expenditure in Latin Am< a. This latter,\nindeed fraught with sensibleness and farseeing American diplo\nmacy. Our nation would indeed do well to look towards the\nNorth (Canada) and the South (through Mexico, Central America\nand South America) for development and Americanidation. With\npiopei use of funds, both private funds and government\nfunds, and with prudent and wise application of Diplomacy, all of\n^-e countries in the Western Hemisphere may eventually be\nought under the flag of the United States, economically, ami\nin fact, governmentally. This part of the program is wise and\nshould be pursued with full speed ahead.\nAs for continuing to pour money and goods into Europe, Asia|\nand Africa with the hope of lifting up and making friends out of\nenemy nations and peoples, the plan is obsurd. In the|\nfirst place, these peoples and countries do not desire to be\nAmericanized as we know the word \".Americanization\", and in the\nsecond place, we have no hope of Americanizing them, either\neconomically or for future armed freindship. These countries\nin the old world will bleed every dollar and every ton of goods Ii\npossible from America and then, should America in the future\nneed their freindship, their backs may be promptly turned Their\nphilosophy of life and their phloophy of government are foreignl\nto ours and are the kind which they live and desire and we are be-j\ning foolhardy in trying to change them.\nIn America we are already faced with a recession in business\nand perhaps a depression which may reach grave proportionsl\nwithin the next three to five years. Millions of American peo-|\nple are already unemployed and possible millions in America may\nsoon be in actual need of food. In fact, there are in America to-'\nday millionswho are not able to have proper clothing and the\nproper kind of food. As the recession and depression increases\nIn intensity, so will the needs and woes and miseries of our own\npeople increase.\nPresdent Truman and his Congress undoubtedly should beginl\nto think of that which may soon come in America and begin now I\nto economize in government expenditures and prepare to, if and I\nwhen necessary, give food, shelter, medicine and clothing to our 1\nown needy Americans.\nUnited Nations Secretary, General Trygve Lie, recently in a\nspeech in America advocated loans or gifts for TVAs and other\nimprovements in foreign countries, particularly Asiatic and\nAfrean countries. His theme was for American money to be\nsent there for such purposes. Of course, such would be wonder\nful and might bring great development and relief to these darken\ned and backward areas, as pointed out by President Truman: how\never, we believe that the United States and the American people\nare not financially able to now go into any such governmental al\ntruistic and charitable enterprises. tet private capital and the\ncharitable capital of private individuals loan themselves to such\nenterprises. Our annual natonal budget now is some forty two\nbillion dollars and the President and the Congress are threatening\nto levy additional and increased taxes to meet this budget. A I\nsmall group of Senators, principally from the South, are uniting I\nin an effort to stave off further taxation and to retrench federall\nexpenditures. They have the vision and the light of future ne-I\nrealties at home. They are undoubtedly correct in their appealsl\nfor economy and should be sustained in such by the American peo\nple. I\nAged American war veterans of World Wars 1 and II have not I\nyet been able to obtain even a small pension when they reach the|\nage of 65. The Congress thus far has denied or failed to pass I\n.uch Legislation. The Congress has also failed to increase u^ I.\nage pensions and social security payments up to a point averag-I\ning as much as one-half of the funds needed by the individual to|\nsustain average living.\nMr. Hoffman of the European Gift Agency is appearing before I\ncommittees of the Congress urging more for Europe, Asia and I\nAfrica, and. when questioned by one of our Senators, McKeller of|\nTennessee, was indignant and caused the Senator to state thatl\nHoffman should resign. Hoffman apparently was not discourag-|\ned but pled for more Atrerican money for foreigners. The in\nfluence and power of the foreign foe within our own government\ndigging in and almost threatenng to take over our American\ngovernmental machinery and treasury for the gifts and upbuild\ning of foreigners and foreign countries. It is time for true\nAmericans to call a Balt to such tactics, appeals and acts which\nthreaten the economic structure of our nation and our treasury\nAi to vote against the reelection of all Congressmen and Sena\ntors who vote for continual gifts of money and goods to foreign\ner and foreign countries.\nBy The-Editor-In-Chief\nlOINI Repair\nIllAOlOService foJ\n|W.B. REDDING\nAcross Street From Courthouse\n\nUNION COUNTY TIMES, LAKE BUTLER, FLORIDA\n\"I'm from Milwaukee\u2014\nI oughtto know... jug\nF\n\ny\nGENE RAYMOND\nI Famous Movie Star c-b--/\nI r ,kfl.^ft. w^ lUty|t^\nFOR COUNCILMAN\nTo The Voters of Lake Butler:\nI take this means of announcing\nmy candidacy for Councilman,\nsubject to the City Election to be\nheld .June 28th., if elected I\npromise to be fair, impartial and\neconomical, always working for\nthe betterment of our town, and\ncitizens to the very best of my\nability.\nYour Friend,\nE. B. Andrews.\nFOR COUNCILMAN\nTo the Voters of Lake Butler.\nI take this means of announc\nling my candidacy for Councilman\nsubject to the City Election to be\nheld June 28th.. 1949. If elect\ned I promise to be Fair, Loyal\nand impartial in the performance\nof my duties.\nJames M. Moore\nLEGAL NOTICE\nIN THE CIRCUIT COURT OF\nFLORIDA IN AND FOR UNION\nCOUNTY, IN CHANCERY.\nGeorge H. Smith,\nPlaintiff,\nvs\nKatherine Elizabeth Smith,\nDefendant.\nORDER OF PUBLICATION ANI\nNOTICE TO APPEAR\nSTATE OF FLORIDA to: Kathej\nrine Elizabeth Smith, 143 West K;\nStreet. Post Office Box 131;\nBenicia, California.\nYou are required to appear or|\nJuly 4th, 1949, in the above nam-I\ned Court and cause, wherein thel\nplaintiff seeks divorce. Union\nCounty Times shall publish thi|\nOrder in the next four weekly;\nissues.\nWITNESS my hand and officia|\nseal at Lake Butler, Florida, this;\n26th day of May, A. D. 1949.\nC. B. Hayes\nAs Clerk of Said Court\nHal Y. Maines,\nLake Butler, Florida\nAttorney for Plaintiff.\nfc &OT\n\"I'm from Milwaukee\u2014\nI ought to know...\nI rf^^re\nsays\nVICTOR McLAGLEN\nFamous Movie Star L\nc and,,\neasy'\nN ks- thcy\nm h CT\u2022\"\n_ (JUST TRY IT)\nBs a fisherman'sl\nearn come true\n.this miracle\nthat takes you\nwhere there's\nto float your I\n'Now yours on I\n'^gfy, 3 great Evinrudes\nSportwin I\n^-^and the 4-cylinder\nZephyr. Call\u2014le +us I\nhelp you choose the model that's j\nright for youlj\nBurrough's Electric\nCompany\nLAKE BUTLER. FLA\nMinutes of the Board\nOf Public Instruction\n(Continued from first page) _\nfor Home Making Education of\nUnion County High School for the\nperiod ending 6-30-49 was ap\nproved.\nFederal Aid for Veterans Train\ning for the Month of May, 1949\nI was approved as a receipt in the\nsum of $86.00.\nAt 200 P. M. the Board was in\nregular session to receive sealed\nbids for the construction of a\n;Gymnasium at Lake Butler,\nJ Florida. The following bids\n:with results noted were received-\nHarry Brownette bid $63,000.00\nH. S. Brownette bid $65,000.00\nDennison Con. Co. bid $62,300.00\n,lEast Coast Con. Co. $60,579.00\nEarl Hunter bid $64,957.00\nI E. C. Kenyon bid $62,952.00\nI Means Con. Co. bid $62,430.00\nA. D. Newkirk bid $63,776.00*\nII Palmer Engineering\nand Con. Co. bid $52,970.0(1\nParker-Giebieg\nConst. Co. bid $68,100.00\nAfter careful consideration it\n;Was moved and carried to tenta+\nLively accept the bid of Palmer\nI Construction Company because it\nwas the lowest bid submitted.\nThis acceptance was contingent\nl upon the posting of a satisfactory I\nperformance Bond of 100 percent\nsof the amount bid. Other bids}\n;were held in abeyance until thel\nI Board could meet again and give|\nj further consideration to the mat-i\nThe following transactions were|\n;audited, approved and warrants|\nI issued for same for the Month i\n;ending 5-31-49.\nI Calendar Monthly Payroll\nScholastic Monthly Payroll\nSupplementary Record of Expend-I\nitures.\n1 hence the Board adjourned.\nATTEST: T. S. Thomas,. Supt.\nT. S. Thomas Salary. $293.31\nState Teachers Retirement\nIFund $16.29\nI Fees-T. S. Thomas $16,291\nI Collector Internal Revenue $40.40;\nI T. J. Dukes Salary $50.001\nM. M. Griffis Salary $50.00;\nMl^ $3,201\nW. L. Brown Salary $50.001\nI Mld $1.60\nI Kilas 